            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-06-11T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-06-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="518"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d518">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">851.01/848</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Delegation of the French National
                            Committee in the United States</gloss> to the <gloss type="to"
                            >Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Translation]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-06-11">June 11,
                            1942</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Referring to its note of May 18, the Delegation of the French National Committee
                    in the United States has the honor to send herewith to the Department of State,
                    by order of the National Committee, the text of a Memorandum<note n="53"
                        xml:id="d518fn53">
                        <hi rend="italic">Infra</hi>.</note> which defines and elaborates the views
                    already expressed in the above-mentioned note on the conditions of Combatant
                    France in the question concerning the war status of the French possessions in
                    America.</p>
                <p>Copy of this communication has been sent to Ambassador Drexel Biddle<note n="55"
                        xml:id="d518fn55">Ambassador to the Polish Government in Exile at London and
                        Minister to the Governments in Exile at London of Czechoslovakia, Greece,
                        the Netherlands, Norway, and Yugoslavia.</note> in London.</p>
            </div>
